The Higgs boson analyzes
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has caused some stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model - our best or "least wrong" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for the physicists, it's not yet entirely certain that it's really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this appears to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data is still missing to be completely safe about it.
Nevertheless, let’s assume that it is actually the Higgs, because there is apparently only a small risk of being mistaken, and let’s look at what it is about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that causes two objects to not be present in the same place at the same time.
It's not possible to violate this rule - and don't try too hard as you'll hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a truly strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli's exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state," with this "state" broadly consisting of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and kindly obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons, a nasty gang of anarchists, who are not sacred to anything - definitely not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure from the Berkeley laboratories (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing), these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle" that is the "messailor" of electromagnetic force.
If a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly at this location, like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" in order for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be smashed by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is not, in fact, all particles and not all the materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't - for example, a piece of paper would never keep on the fridge by itself.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do possess a mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) do not possess mass.
For what can all this research be "good," Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, they serve to verify the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to closely study all the deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are, by the way, numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes of the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great shortcomings, since it offers no explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which is approx. 80% of the matter of the universe forms (renewed ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found in the CERN.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be none.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous stroke laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was initially regarded more as a "lab play."
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the tools that surround research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you can never really know...
