A constitution with the crowbar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which grants him the unrestricted power of attorney, he has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the constituent assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this plenary two additional months to complete his work.
Egypt has now been relying on a preliminary, multiple-changed text for nearly two years, weakening institutional stability and leading to a legal mess.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "trample on the right."
On the part of its proponents, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain to the Egyptians the text section by section.
For the president, it is also a way of finding his public and democratic legitimacy again, while the protest is raging across the country.
After reaffirming in an interview with the American newsreel Time, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will be benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to a hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited authority," the latter should supposedly come to an end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constituent assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals have not complied with the request.
Shortly before the declaration of constitution in mid-November, they turned away, as they believe they have not been able to bring their views to fruition.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
To achieve the quorum, 11 people, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly passed unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, found it entertaining that the only disagreement of the day... at the time for the prayer was expressed, since some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the constituent assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, finally remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, saying that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of justice."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules," which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and to their respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrine" is what the liberals, who see this only as a propaganda strike, return.
According to them, the Islamization of the constitution is done via other articles.
In particular, they have Article 220 in mind, which grants the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing, as "the people who are asked to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
You can see the first signs of theocracy in this.”
The fears of the Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
"Currently, no concrete religious commitment can be seen.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema, but academics who have been partly trained in the French system," appeases Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, "that there may be an ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
It refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, ed. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide on it."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticized for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wish of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations for the defense of human rights have called for.
The latter also share their fears regarding the text, which they regard as freedom-threatening.
The fact of blasphemy is maintained, and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, particularly to the press.
In addition, no more article refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites within itself the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and an untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five most important reasons to visit Israel.
Bowing to the holy sites
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all those who bathe in this river receive God’s blessings.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding celebration, walking on the water, the satisfying of the seastorm and fishing.
Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries are found in Jerusalem.
Believers celebrate the path of suffering here. Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to Christian opinion, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands in the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree grew, from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is also the holiest place of the Jews - the Western Wall, the remains of a temple, the one by the Romans in the year 70 n. Chr. was destroyed.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a trip to the heights
The ruins of the fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hideout from enemies, the Herod of the Great in the year 25 n. Christ had built for his family.
They are located on a rock face in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else is taking an air cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters, the famous ski resort Hermon is located, where it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods allegedly lived on the mountaintop.
Visiting unique museums
There are nearly 300 museums in this country.
With just one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum not far from the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or Scrolls of the Dead Sea, found in rock caves in the Judean Desert, are kept, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There, the collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso will be exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers of the time.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum. Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most harrowing chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the memorial to the children, built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
Upon entering the room, there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And it is heard the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and ocean arias.
Amazingly, the Red Sea also bathes in the winter months, because the water temperature there does not drop below 21 °C and the air heats up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there is bathing throughout the year.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the lowest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and therefore even carries non-swimmers on the surface without any problems.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt sols) and healing mud, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to calmed nerves.
Touching the secrets of antiquity
These secrets are held by the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city ran the famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda here, with which he led a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
Fortuna is said to be, according to legend, all hold that touches the walls in the alley with its zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even other countries at photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In the Roman period, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre, evening concerts and operas are performed today.
Watchlist for tourists
If you are going to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English proficiency: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is not taken in euros, but in dollars, which can simply be changed to shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually make progress by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed tram and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which is enough including changing trains for a trip of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is observed in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday night until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is resting.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and food that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, deep-fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
There are many well-nourished cats that stray through the streets comfortably and unmolested.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don't say no to treats.
A rental car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) to 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
Insurance costs an additional 15 dollars per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
Most of the adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the US and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Country, which corresponds to an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the cancellation of the visa requirement on the 9th. February 2011.
"The big and powerful" leads to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading in fake allowances
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families remaining in the home country.
On 1. In December, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this regulation only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, the municipal housing industry and the retail trade.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests should become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
You have to take not only language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both receipt and renewal of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who have received their training certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
The totality of the examination bodies will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, the Moscow State University, the Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; more than 160 corresponding centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law came into force in the press: What does the whole thing actually mean?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, counters spokespersons for the migration authority, it is a matter of reducing the number of forced laborers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says the head of the representation of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebelev.
However, their rights must be protected from their departure.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems are encountered by migrants without a profession, education, language skills and medical evaluation.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who will put him in a dark, narrow barrack under the pretext of help, where he will endure with dozens of similar months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"At home, you will be promised the one, and on arrival you will be cheated, their passports will be taken and will not receive the promised wages," confirms the head of the main administration for labour migration of the Tajik migration authority, Tolib Shvaripov.
Don't scold, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to earn their money in Russia, admit that they not only do not master the language of the destination country, but can hardly express themselves in their own language in writing.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a reasonable primary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect regarding the law.
Only migrants with legal status have to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and consequently no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers continue to be in Russia illegally.
"Welcome" or "access for unauthorized persons prohibited"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be done quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The employees of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly forged and we are not registered, and this then results in cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," the Tajike Umed Hushkadamov told journalists.
"Just don't shy away from costs for false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be fake.
Some fake certificates that certify the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive these for nothing: Every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
That's more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this one costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights activists agree on the fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time that they will be given time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where no active communication with people is necessary.
Home Office ignores illegal gun market
Proportion of legal weapons in crimes extremely low
The Russian Interior Ministry is planning to tighten the gun law for private gun owners.
The authorities are responding to the recent events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the rampage of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov.
Police want to ban the carrying of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21.
The proposal was supported by the chairwoman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarowaja, and promised that the amendments to the gun law would be presented to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "attracting the screws."
An open letter was published on the Internet, the authors - representatives of various weapons associations - demand from the authorities to refrain from "senseless tightening".
The percent of crimes involving registered weapons is very minor, the criminal lawyer, Vaily Lesnikov, told the BBC's Russian service.
According to the Ministry of the Interior statistics, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed over the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1.168 thousand offences were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not stop criminals from using themselves on the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors, you can find every possible weapon for little money in Moscow.
Meanwhile, the Home Office stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a web page that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. Weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez says.
On the second channel come illegal weapons that order guards are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons that were stolen from both the police armory and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons depots.
Many military camps often caused explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military official says.
According to Baranez, the weapons manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private armaments factories that do not withstand international competition and therefore squander the weapons under the hand on the black market, for example in Moscow," reports the expert.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries like Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a separate, sometimes craft production as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the proportion of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was written by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on portals on the subject of weapons.
The majority of the illegal weapons, according to investigators, come from the army and the legal protection authorities.
Half of all weapons on the black market were there through the "debt of those responsible who dealt with guns in their work," the report said.
According to the researchers' data, 17% of the weapons come from conflict zones, 14% are due to thefts in weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales adviser to a gun shop who doesn't want to be named assures that guns found during illegal excavations have long since been buying no one because they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get supplies in a weapons depot.
A gun, for example a gun of the type TT, is purchased via an ensign.
