De facto, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"Mars and Venus," says the research associate of the Astronomical Sternberg Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, that is, in space.
The researchers first dealt with the question of reproduction in space with regard to the flora.
Already half a century before that, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of the peas bred in orbit did not differ in the least from the earthly species.
This was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely from tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to explore how microgravity affects embryo development.
A normal chick is developing.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to find a hold; it must be able to stand on its feet and start moving," explains the laboratory manager of the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychew.
Without a solid ground, the chicks overturned wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns dulled completely.
The chicks did not respond to light and sound.
Four days later, they simply died.
"Twice we let chicks slip and then stopped the whole thing, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychev notes on the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be found on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that had already been sent into space fertilized.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"That was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research must continue," notes Vladimir Sychew.
After the landing, the space rats got offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn from their natural habitat simply cannot follow their propagation drive.
Unlike animals, humans could do this in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical considerations, such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was at Terezhkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive the space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"After all, no one answered that question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just a year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Terezhkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andriyan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawitskaya, who was in orbit twice and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Still, a risk remains.
We have very few cosmonauts, where everything went well after long flights and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even on flights into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valery Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
