The competences are also comparable to a certain extent, but Germany is a federal state, i.e. that these Courts of Auditors also exist in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The BRH may only control federal funds, which corresponds to our state funds.
Public funds, which are managed by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the state audit courts.
As for German legislation, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would be reluctant to compare this without specific information. Nevertheless, Germany is often referred to as a role model in some respects, but it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is that because the examiners are better there?
I don’t like that, but as I said, I don’t like to make such comparisons.
It should also be noted that those countries that are an example for us also have to deal with problems.
Otherwise, they would have nothing to cooperate with our authority, would they?
As for the Czech legislation, the significance for your authority was the amendment of the Public Procurement Act, do you feel any effect?
Given that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had an impact on our examinations.
Since our checks take place retrospectively, a certain delay must be expected here.
We have so far felt the implications rather in the preparatory phase of future checks - so we have introduced the new control instrument "Recognition of risks of uneconomicity" and with this almost 14,000 public contracts examined and analysed - here the changes will of course have an impact, since the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, etc.
Do you see the passage of this law rather positively, or will the system be burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction and hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be adhered to.
Already under the previous rules, the persons subject to an examination are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) in such a way that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act is equivalent to a violation of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I don't think so in this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making.
Such a system puts only bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
First, let’s say which path is not expedient.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS did not provide the entrepreneurs with checks of the so-called. "Black system" would bother - what does that mean exactly?
Is the black system now banned or allowed?
A law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then the head of the government cannot simply come, and the control office, whose duty is now the control of compliance with the law, hinder in his activity.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the matter," but he can't say we're pretending nothing.
The Public Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain processes - and this is also correct for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded due to formal errors alone.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think we lack.
