Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to gather positive energy
What do you think about the fact that the doomsday is to take place in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we people so like to jump on.
With our band The Tap Tap, we're more likely to make fun of it and say we're the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It is a nationwide charity event, which we have been planning for two years.
For this, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, the end of which for the 21. December at 11:10 a.m. is forecast.
The day before, i.e. on 20. December, three concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 21:00.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be around the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a 12-hour time zone ahead of us.
Who did this idea come from?
Originally probably from me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic artist Honza Augusta.
We not only want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we hand over this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and keychains against the doomsday, with the purchase of which people can also support us via www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap, together with other performers, also has the so-called. Hymn against the end of the world entitled "Doomsday falls out" recorded.
The anthem is already very popular on YouTube. Will she also resound at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and the end of the world does not take place...
The anthem is to be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the anthems will be broadcast live together in a direct circuit from Czech television.
The lyrics of the hymn come from Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of the Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to work with both of you?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many benefit events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most are interested in working with us, and enjoy it.
What purpose does the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world benefit?
For the establishment of the barrier-free education center Studeo, where we have been working together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute for six years.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by editors who help them with different leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the editors, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be built, into which we will move with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
What criteria did you use to select them?
We wanted to put together a program that appeals to all generations including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý perform.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "large events" also planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and we will also be preparing an interesting program with interesting guests for this concert.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - this would also like to combine with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not exactly small, so far you have already appeared in Madrid, Brussels, London or in Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. In addition, of course, we have to carry a lot of instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes wondered in part.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your trips abroad, you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than ours, we were just witnessing in Russia that everything in the East is still in its beginnings.
Opposite Prague, Moscow is absolutely not accessible for the disabled. There it is still unusual when someone in a wheelchair is traveling alone in the city center.
It is not even a matter of course that you leave a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, clubs are also emerging there that are trying to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what respect do we need to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still many things in which we hang behind...
In addition, however, it should be noted that an improvement in the situation always depends on the effort of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to be able to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
However, it is not exactly common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in the social events, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in public and accessibility is one thing, but it is only when significant athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks that things really will start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular right now. But if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in dealing with something intensively.
And since I am a musician myself and, among other things. Saxophone games, I founded a music company together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our moderator, Láďa Angelovič, likes to say, is a bit out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that the collaboration with well-known singers has helped us; we also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and this is not visible to the outside world, your own performance does not exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good proofreaders, high-quality equipment and the like.
Was it your goal to get it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to be able to approach things differently.
In show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and is only accepted after a long time.
There are few truly unique things, and I dare say that tap tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is of course pity; this is only natural...
But this pity is absolutely superfluous because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we would have to regret.
They are people who live and can develop a full-fledged life, provided they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed, this is not only progress for themselves, but for the whole of society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from a lot of people?
If you want to do something well, you must not compromise on many things and must also demand a certain discipline.
In my opinion, this is completely normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and if they then find that they have rehearsal twice a week, have to complete preparation phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, then the enthusiasm of many quickly extinguishes.
But that’s how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of these were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Just one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group. People come and go. You can't prevent that.
Who has the will and the desire to participate, is always welcome with us.
