Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted to a Council of Ministers meeting of the member countries of the European Space Agency ESA as the twentieth member of this space agency. Poland is thus the second member country from the former Eastern Bloc (to the Czech Republic, which will take place on 12 December. November 2008 ESA member).
Poland began a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s path to space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts dealt with space travel, whereby they did not always come across understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture of A. Šternfeld of 6. December 1933 in the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) left the audience cold, however, and after years Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, in 1934 for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski’s globally recognized contribution to the development of space travel was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the earth-facing side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
The author of the draft and the details of this project unfortunately remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or brake the draisine.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered projectiles.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the documents that the research had penetrated to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the von Ing. Rohoziński's design of a photoelectric hunting rocket, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the missile propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work his work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Agency (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society is in the November issue of the magazine Problemy in 1954, in which four extensive articles of space travel are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was foreseeable that the exploration of space would have a future.
Already in its early days in 1956, the Polish Space Company PTA sought to join the International Federation of Spaceflight, which was founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member as early as the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became deputy chairman of the International Federation of Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch was made on the 10th. October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight altitude of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, flight tests began in the Błędów Desert with the two-stage rocket RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high-altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was stopped.
The first RM missiles were followed by the Meteor 1 rocket, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the take-off weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) that differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor 1A rocket had a transport space with a capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B had 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum altitude for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aeronaus Institute developed the Meteor 2 rocket, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a take-off weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of approximately 60 km.
After that, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Also worth mentioning is the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
