The MVRDV architects prove that the real adventures are not only in the head - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there's something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a roadside passer-by.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large company, says: "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder what we still need a library for today.
All have internet, iPad and e-books.
No one still volunteers to go to one of these old-style libraries today, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping city in need of sightseeing just outside Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant community has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to the general education and to recreate the seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on the euro bills, as beautifully painted reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master the statistics: A library must come!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of the daring bar charts and producer of funny, even often cynical buildings, took the matter with the usual serenity and appeared for the competition hearing anno 2003 with five books under the arm and a grin on the face.
And while the jury was still looking around and shrugging with its armpits, the cheeky Meuse stacked up his exquisite souvenirs of the size to a pyramid and ended his actionist underpinned speech with the words: "Dear city community!"
So this is he, my suggestion for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain, which cost 30 million euros, is poured.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
Thus, the faceless small-town retort, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunned ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory is richer in order to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Road to the Book
The first impression: bookel dorado under cheese bell.
There is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the true pleasures of space and reading are revealed when climbing the topography on foot.
The all-round glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant streetlights clearly speak the language of a public town square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already on the lookout for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
Books, books, books, books everywhere.
"Normally the bookshelves stand along the facade, and in the middle lies a large, dark room, which is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We have turned the classic room configuration upside down and turned the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and building technology headquarters.
A special joy are the black bookcases, which are sometimes wall coverings, sometimes parapets, sometimes staircase railings.
Optics, feel and smell are foreign.
Even die-hard architects and civil engineers shake their heads at the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work here with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the Standard.
And so we in a Frisian farm one day came across a suitable waste product from agriculture.
For many years, a millimeter-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root pad in greenhouses in the Netherlands and in fields.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece was pressed - for the first time in these quantities - to four centimeters thick plates.
Under the action of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) discolors into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells a bit of a new car and a bit of a sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-meter-long hike, the Literaturcafé not only offers a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
Heating and cooling is carried out with geothermal energy.
Although the book mountain is under a glass fall, the sun shines only briefly inside even on sunny days.
The wide wood glue binders, which stand transversely to the glass facade, serve as shading and intercept a large part of the sunlight.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, was already making his way to the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes the Boekenberg as a Spijkenisses "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, every resident was invited to donate a book from his personal holdings.
For the time being, this is intended to fill the optical gaps in the library, which is not yet fully equipped, currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept has worked.
The shelves are filled to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that their book is part of this building.
And if it's just to the ornament.
In this way, MVRDV has succeeded in achieving the supreme discipline that is called identity foundation in the technical jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
