Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most foul-smelling fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living - and not only in Europe, but all over the world.
Could the country's secret of success have anything to do with the local appetite for pretty foul-smelling fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
You place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, wet sportswear.
And leave them there for a week.
That's how you have to imagine the nose-defying smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway's great delicacies.
I am located in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There's snow here, spectacular landscapes - and that stubborn smell in the air that just doesn't want to go away.
Rakfisk is salt-sprinkled trout, which - depending on how smelly you would like your fish - is fermented in water for up to a year.
When darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, dedicated to this, well, really very captivating specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works at the local fire station, but also hosts the festival as a so-called "Rakfisk general."
Around us, people eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
"Some people like the aquavit more than the rakfisk," Havard says.
The spirit can displace the smell.
I'm tasting some bites.
If you avoid bringing the rakfisk close to the nose, it is not bad - like sushi, which has a quite long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a very different, far poorer Norwegian era than there were no cooling options yet and fish was soaked in airtight saltwater barrels in autumn.
In the deepest winter, he was then taken out after a long fermentation and - undoubtedly under senses subdued with the help of alcohol - consumed.
Even a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and mainly emigrated to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labor market, high wages and a comprehensive healthcare system.
