Rakfisk is seen as something important - as an essential, if strictly smelling, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the more expensive dishes to buy here.
But actually everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs a proud 10 euros.
Norway doesn't often make it into the world press, and most people don't seem to mind that.
Here you still hate to call Anders Breivik by name - that racist right-wing extremist who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, one refers only to the "incident of 22. July."
Norwegians find it difficult to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
The main responsibility for Norway's wealth today has been the growth of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries since the early 1970s.
"But oil isn't the only reason why we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays with mature rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and pungent blue eyes.
We are a - as they say - prudent people.
Their English is just like that of most people here flawless.
We're not very showy, we don't like boasting.
Norway has been very cautious about its oil wealth - a large proportion of industry earnings are invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the Great Depression, everyone threw money around them that they did not even own, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And, of course, eat rakfisk," she adds with carefree laugh.
I'm standing in the snow and lining up for another dish - I've had enough of Rakfisk.
Such a moose burger is definitely something else. The juicy meat mouths me.
But in the evening, the stink fish is on the menu again.
The hotel I'm staying at is one of several venues that organize a rakfisk dinner where guests can tune for the best - or perhaps the senses of smell most challenging - fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a bow tie-clad showmaster surrounded by plates of rakfisk.
The spectacle is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
You clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the Aquavit.
But maybe it's the hard haze of all the fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces tough start
As Mexico's future president, Enrique Pena Nieto, prepares to take office, Will Grant of the BBC analyses the challenges ahead and his people's mixed feelings.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad.
Even on better days, this is an always clogged city, but on Monday a ring of steel was erected, which blocks several important traffic routes to the capital and causes chaos on the streets.
The goal, however, was not to disrupt commuters on their way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will be given the presidential tie and take over the nation's leadership.
He faces a complex task.
Under the outgoing Felipe Calderon government, Mexico has proven itself economically well, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
"My administration is strongly committed to reducing violence," Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy with which we can achieve this goal.
Before he went on an equal footing with the US president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, sprawling part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions are divided about the new head of state.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember it.
Residents of the holiday resort attribute to him the development of tourism and the construction of the infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built and which represent a great improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques with its name also hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and lasting changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who as a congressman for the party Pena Nietos, which works PRI.
In particular, as far as security and the economy are concerned, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so desperately needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party is setting great expectations for Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects the opposition's accusations that the new president lacks substance.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share that view about their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the paved streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway overpasses and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are crucially urban in nature.
Earlier this year, the military was turned on to fight drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
On a patch of wasteland near a large landfill, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left behind in the last two years alone.
During Governor Pena Nieto's tenure, over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that itself surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
The critics of Pena Nieto are of the opinion that he has at least not adequately addressed the problem of women's murders during his tenure.
But in the worst case, his government has closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the run-down neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears as she shows me photos of her late daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her significant other.
"When I arrived at her home, it seemed like her body had been washed," recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs she was beaten, and the body stare had already set in.
While her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall. It is appropriate next to a cross that carries a single word: justice.
But this, according to the family, has been denied to her until now.
The authorities treated me as if I was a chatterer, troublemaker, nag.
They want their judgment to simply be accepted and mouth shut.
"But that's not possible when there were so many formal errors and failings," she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential tie on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crime in the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this issue during his tenure.
"I hope as president he is the way he was as governor," says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that is exactly what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of.
The prosecution claims: Bradley Manning has not complained about mistreatment
The prosecution contradicts Bradley Manning's allegations that he was abused in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time at the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense is seeking a rejection of the charge based on harsh conditions of detention
The U.S. Army private is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
The prosecution on Friday tried to establish that Army-free Bradley Manning - charged with the biggest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history - failed to face several opportunities to complain about the abuse he allegedly suffered in military custody.
At a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland explained to Maj. Ashden Fein, that documents on weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month detention period in Quantico, Virginia, had no complaints whatsoever about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to reject the charge - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard prison term - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then posted by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In Friday's hearing, Fein went through with Manning the forms that officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his detention at Quantico military prison, where he had been in force from July 2010 to April 2011 under heightened prison conditions.
Officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein questioned him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged treatment by his guards to be "excellent" and treatment by the facility as "very professional" overall.
The forms, according to Fein, did not include any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers had questioned Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that he was dealing with them. However, they were not logged.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) "No problems," and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 that was to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to reduce his observational status to "prevent injuries."
The military testified that it assigned him this restrictive status - which is one step under the risk of suicide - to his and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and getting rid of the observational status for the prevention of injuries (...) in order to be able to achieve a higher quality of life in my view," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marine base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and had once fallen unconscious due to the heat.
Not to be allowed to know what was happening to him or in the outside world was burdensome.
"My world shrank on Camp Arafjon, on this cage together," Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without society.
He was allowed only a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to keep moving, because the day it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He always had to sleep with light, which penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and waking guards could no longer see his face, he was woken up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the Fort Leavenworth, Kansas military prison.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an allegation he made in his testimony on Thursday - so he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to envelop himself with his blanket during this count.
During the questioning on Friday, Manning said he had closed out of an order from his guard that he should drop the ceiling with which he could have covered. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night. He would have previously tried to show an official that he poses no danger to himself.
Manning had told the official he could have used the waistband of his underpants or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not do so.
That night, Manning testified, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his prison experiences and drastically reduce his detention if he is convicted at his trial in the military court. This is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to minor offenses, while other charges deemed too extreme are to be contested.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend. The prosecution is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions that apply to all detainees kept under the highest security precautions in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include the enemy's favoritism, unlawful publication of intelligence on the Internet, the transmission of national defense information and theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he faces a life sentence.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to accuse the emigrants - they remind them of hard times, he says
Navarrette believes that Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when perplexity spread in me.
Signs referred to two queues: One for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure which one to go to.
I grew up in Central California and have been called "Mexicans" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Iren" or my friends in New York "Italians."
Later, I chose "Mexican-American."
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's home, there was no need for shortcuts or hyphens.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I can't get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for Extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those issues you expect when the minds of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy. It is one reason why Mexicans are equally likely to stay in Mexico these days rather than emigrate to the United States.
He wants to team up with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc modeled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico's war on the drug cartels, even if he did not give details in this regard.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country's leadership under a gunpoint to leave more than half of their territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries rather than minutes, memories of this event cannot be overlooked.
So once a U.S. government official makes even mildest criticism of Mexico, one hears - in the Mexican press and among the country's elites - complaints about how Americans are afflicting the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma are on the war path.
And yet Mexico's biggest challenge is in truth the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. People for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is because at one point in our family tree, a person - perhaps a parent or grandparent - was offered no chance in Mexico and emigrated to the north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our faithfulness is for them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may now live the American dream, have attended good schools and received good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we live - not the Mexican one.
Our identity may be blurry sometimes, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
Moreover, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership class do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial to a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have gone.
And then we wouldn't see ourselves trapped now behind the silk curtain - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans resent them.
While she is an American citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
Yet many Mexican Americans I know feel they belong neither to one country nor to the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but none of them are rooted.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to resume their ties to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as makeshift "ambassadors" for Mexico, which represents their interests in the United States.
We are to tell our American colleagues about how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well, well.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unjust distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if it is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through it alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans hold a grudge for how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to nip such hope in the bud.
In the midst of the usual blame, countless buildings were reduced to rubble, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed - and for the first time, rockets from Gaza near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem have struck.
Yet even though Israelis and Palestinians appear trapped in their historic conflict, the Middle East around them is changing.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not - Palestinians and Israelis have become part of these turmoils.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems anything but appropriate given the current situation.
Even if he on 21. November agreed ceasefire continues, this week's fighting has strengthened the hard-pressed on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, even though his grouping itself has suffered large losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are cooped up in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders could conclude that they have the time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a resurgent, regional power once considered Israel's closest Muslim ally, has taken sides for Hamas - just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Jubilant Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, over Syria, where rebels could face an increasingly Islamist imprint before the fall of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt - by far the most populated and most important Arab country - on the southern flank of Israel has permanently changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his 2011 overthrow, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is more in-perfect with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, make an opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a danger.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome," has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
For at least a while, Israel will be able to sleep more quietly.
In diplomatic terms, the United States is unwaveringly sticking to its position. Many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest violence escalations.
Israel has fared well in recent years, particularly under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers - not least thanks to the lockdown facilities that run into the West Bank and thus into the bulk of any Palestinian state. These protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared contrary to international law, but are being expanded further and further.
Netanyahu is in a good position. His Likud party has itself in the run-up to the elections on 22. January under Avigdor Lieberman allied with an even more combative group.
Why do these devious Palestinians also coddle and leave them their own state?
If they actually had control of the West Bank, would they not fire rockets, just like their fellow Gazans?
No, it's better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them should they dare to raise their heads.
Maybe the hardliners will be able to prevail. But the Arab Spring could make a dash through their account.
Even if the Islamists, who are now in power in Egypt and in other countries, have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel's defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments in repairing their economies.
That the pragmatic President Morsi teamed up with Barack Obama to reach a cease-fire could be an auspicious sign - and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should think more long-term, too.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking tentative steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination - a powder keg that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to push back Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly take their diplomatic toll over the years.
Both sides need an impetus from the outside
The correct answer is the one represented by the more rational representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states where Israel is ceding territories for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will grant outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms supplies to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever before to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by territorial exchange and a common Jerusalem.
Outside Arab nations should also persuade Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would be more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the imminent request for UN observer status.
Obama, too, must do his part to persuade Israel to engage in negotiations.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the white house, it seems as if he is also averse to involvement.
But this is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a significant interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws on uniform cigarette packaging come into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world's first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia. This replaces brand logos and colors with neutral, olive green lids, which are also printed with drastic images that show sick body parts and cigarette smoke-sick infants and children.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packs in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font, will be there from next Saturday.
Australia is thus introducing the world’s strictest regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to dissuade young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
The government assumes studies that have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at 26 will not start with a 99% probability even after that.
"You can already see in children of young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek. She cites studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have little impact on multinational corporations' profits, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It said that the laws would favour black market trade, leading to cheaper and more easily accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences," says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the unbearable packaging has risen enormously since the British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed two months ago at the Supreme Court of Australia with their appeal of the laws.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new holdings.
