In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored
This Thanksgiving, I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane dropped out due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to make myself a few thoughts about boredom.
I don't wanna lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is pretty annoying - even if books, magazines and iPhones (and, of course, tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts cite boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it's okay for us - and our children - to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to get lost in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us these days are almost constantly staring at one or the other screen, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yeah. Yeah.
And no. No.
That's what I'm coming back to.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) doesn't see it that way.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
Pompeii's house walls adorn a Latin graffiti over boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfactory activity, but not be able to do so".
Boredom differs from apathy so that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In apathy, on the other hand, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a "disruption of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is slowly passing."
Boredom can sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored individuals see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed individuals see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even if we're just having trouble focusing.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in German: "The idle mind: The definition of boredom under the aspect of attention", which appeared in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science" in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content. Others listened to it at low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The individuals who heard the barely audible television said they felt more boredom than the other two groups - they had trouble focusing, could find no reason for these and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When trying to focus on a difficult or exhausting task, the disruption of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
If, on the other hand, one carries out a monotonous activity - "just like the search for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that fidgeting and scribbling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even combat them by keeping people more physically attentive.
"Studies have shown that children allowed to hammer around learn more and retain more information than those forced to sit still," according to Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a booming loudspeaker, a particularly tiresome movie.
But some people are more bored than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "scale to susceptibility to boredom" in the 1980s.
On the scale, statements can be found such as "A lot of things I have to do, repeat and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything."
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys become boring more often than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - particularly in terms of the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty strained bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adolescents in school and in doing homework were bored, while 23% said they were bored when they were not in school.
Yet only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know whether the percentages have risen or decreased in terms of boredom.
However, he is sure that "the youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have a great influence on their everyday routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall into gambling or drugs to alleviate them - studies have shown that.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity. This is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the topic for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something different," said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what best to do right now.
If you're bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you get happy.
But television can cause happiness in the short term, but these evaporate again in the long term.
So if you extend an iPad to your bored child, you can take it off the boredom. However, it has not learned to entertain or control itself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control is transferred from one situation to another."
The child not only learns to talk, but also receives more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we see them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even away from the constant activity and technology sprinkling.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“It sounds like we have to be bored more often. But boredom is the excruciating, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth, people are only looking for a way to switch off and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated, it is difficult to keep busy once the noise has fallen silent."
