The most difficult profession in the world: the human workhorses of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and their health at risk when they carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who deserve their lives by extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he must descend every day to the bottom of his crater, where the sulfur-containing gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping paths of stone.
Although it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes for the ascent at the turtle tempo, keeping the balance and taking their steps carefully so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen years ago.
The mining workers of Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
Once at the top, they make their way between the tourists, who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiresomely heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale, which a mining company has set up a little further down at a height of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which since 1960 has exploited the deposits in the volcano and (never better said) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilo of sulfur.
This is what she then sells for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to produce matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each way," explains Anto, who usually does three routes a day.
For each route he needs three hours, after which he is completely done, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable reward for such an almost inhuman effort, however, is three times what he would earn with field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid on the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros) is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, and for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as the sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought them to Java to convert them to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been putting his life on the line for three years at the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already left the first traces on him, even though he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for reaching his dream.
"I will work here for another two years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in a more than acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent, but life-sufficient young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter, or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a carrier.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and gets up every morning at two o'clock, because the sulfur also pours out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the darkness.
The shadows challenging, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
About 400 carriers load the baskets on their shoulders with sulfur on the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized the sulfur mining to save costs, and does not supply any equipment to the carriers who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
You also do not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera, which the guardians of this nature park, together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), demand from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrier spre use.
"This work is for the animals and not for humans," protests Madrusin, a stocky, 42-year-old carrier who has worked for three decades since leaving school at the Kawah Ijen.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as he can" because he needs the money to raise his three children, aged between 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
Even when the sulfur burns the throat and the eyes itch, when the wind suddenly turns and pinches the miners in the thick columns that rise from the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains of serious illness ... of course, except the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have deformed from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik, at 53, is only able to carry 50 kg.
Every day, he and his companions break 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks via a goat path between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari at a distance of 18 kilometers.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, where some teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the oldest, at the age of 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty endures generation to generation in one of the hardest professions in the world: that of those who work as human donkeys at the Kawah Ijen.
Singapore needs babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame for not having children, on the career, stress and cost of real estate and child-rearing.
“The people of Singapore need to grow.”
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife: let us fulfill our civic duty and we create life!
It seems unbelievable that the verses are part of an advertisement for mint candies, but nevertheless - or precisely because of it - they became a viral video on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The sentences are part of a rapper song that reads local sayings such as e.g. B. "Pushing a "bao" (loaf) into the oven to make fun of the low birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising company BBH, which shot the video, maintains the hope that the commercial will reach out in a funny way to draw attention to the problem.
