This is just for the Internet, so we had to make it funny and funny.
This is the biggest problem in this country.
When it comes to reproducing, we are the worst in the world, so we realized that it is a topic we had to take care of.
We knew that the government had tried a lot, such as B. the marketing of perfume with pheromones or the organization of speed dating evenings (fast flirts).
It is possible that many of these ideas were creative, but they did not necessarily lead to success.
Therefore, we thought: Why don’t we do something as creative as possible to address this problem, such as B. Composing a rap?
1.2 children
Those who do not take this issue easily are the government of Singapore.
Every year, it spends US$1,300 on policy measures to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents grants up to 15,000 dollars per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has had little success so far.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city-state in southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time that rate was above 2 - which is also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the national population authority, says this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities."
"This has allowed people to have substantially more options in terms of life goals and set priorities, except to marry and form a family," she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the higher number of single people and to the delay of marriage and birth, the result of which is the reduction of the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in immigration to counteract the reduction of the population led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the barely concealed xenophobia flourishes against many new immigrants, especially against the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons the ruling party in Singapore achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known impact on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health care costs and immigration policy, the Singapore example also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to ensure that not so many small apartments are built.
So it already has an impact on the housing market.
The Authority for Urban Development has begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" and allowed to be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living space of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the lifestyle of the single person, and that they are deterring the construction companies from building large housing for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, general manager of the real estate firm EL Developers, says that its "shoe boxes" can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out by days and even weeks faster than the larger housing units.
This causes them to be much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards give developers clearer orientations that were previously placed obstacles in the way if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way to an increase in the national birth rate, it can be seen from the conversations with the Singaporeans who work in the financial district that they will not have much effect.
"People are severely stressed, the apartments and also the upbringing are expensive, which is why it is pushed out by many," says a young manager.
The children can have others.
"For me, it's important to have my own money and time," says another, roughly twenty-year-old man.
Men and women cite their careers, stress and cost of ownership and upbringing as reasons they cannot have children.
That's why Singaporeans have the final say when it comes to having children - the government can still do so much.
The offline private offline is private online
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "the area of private life where you are entitled to protection against any kind of interference."
What is private for someone under 16?
How is this definition applied to his everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he exposes himself to when he makes known on the Internet situations that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five teenagers between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequently on the net.
In four of the cases, they linked the term to "something very own" on a personal level and "to the password and the user" when they applied it to the social networks.
"My deepest secrets I wouldn't announce in a post," says 10-year-old Jorge while trying to explain the importance of "privately" in web pages like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he's had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother is allowed to know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I also spend my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that's not of me, or of someone who makes the fool," he says.
The boy is clear that it is wrong to post obscene photos, of naked people, of crimes, or of insulting or violent comments.
Jorge assures to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers in Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Including the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up on Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone answers me, I just upload them," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can quickly talk to relatives in the distance or with friends," he states.
Asked, he replies that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown.
Even if someone recommends him a stranger, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask, he admits not knowing 20 of the people he has added to his friends list.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, for example music," he states.
According to the boy, no one made him hint or asked him for his address or phone number.
"If someone is oppressing me or asking them to do it from me, I'll just remove it from my user account," he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unfamiliar with experiences that are now known as cyberbullying.
The acquaintance of a friend was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never found out who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim did not close the user account.
"He only did it in private."
After that, he explains a series of steps to securely configure a user account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I would do that if he's unsympathetic to me or I want to wipe him one.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English with a university degree in education and learning, thinks that in order to orient the children and young people, it must be understood that it is the purpose of social networks to inform.
"The Internet emerged as a medium for the search for information; but with the appearance of these pages, the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that the academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master's degree in pedagogy at Yale University and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants" formed these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who are supposed to teach them, when we are still learning ourselves," he said.
He explains that it is a complex issue "because we require them to have a defined criterion about what is allowed to spread, publish or be said, and this at an age where maturity is not sufficient for it."
"They're also supposed to be picky when they're most important to being popular, having thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the professional, the most effective way to teach the children and young people what privacy is is to ask them questions that makes them think.
"To tell them not to do it, doesn't work," he says.
Porras then mentions some possibilities: There are things you would not tell a stranger. Why do you do it on the internet?
Or: Would you like it when you publish a photo of you, like the one you published by a friend?
Do you know what the others are posting about you?
Have you asked the other people for permission before when you have labeled photos of celebrations?
And one more question: Do everyone need to know what you do at every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they need to act online as they do offline.
They are the same rules.
"Someone outside the internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to the social networks," he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educational counselor, comments that it is imperative that parents carefully read through the guidelines of the social networks.
When they understand all the sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, the age, or what you are allowed to share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children must be reminded of the lesson "You shall not speak to strangers."
Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6. Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and should theoretically be signed by the seven rulers present.
Efe repeatedly tried to access the signed document with the VI. To obtain a proper meeting of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasur. Sources at the State and Presidential Chancellery initially said they would hand it over after the exam, but explained afterwards that it would be published at some time on the Peruvian government's website.
In case of questions about the text, they stated that the content was set out by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information on the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio."
The little information circulated among the journalists was obtained from the press spokespersons of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press secretary.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets calling for more information.
After that, the President of Peru sent the media an e-mail with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the declaration of Humala and not the official document at the conclusion of the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the III. Summit South America - Arab States (ASPA), and also on this occasion, despite strong calls by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced before, was also not published.
On the official website of the ASPA, you can see for yourself that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems were in place for the journalists, but they limited access to information to a large extent.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a ruling by the Court of Justice of The Hague, which settles a border conflict between the two countries.
Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICJ, which begins in The Hague on Monday, in the process that Lima launched against Santiago, to hear the pleas from both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are currently making to this international court of justice," Humala said along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will continue to be a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to the international courts," Piñera adds, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia filed an action against the Bogotá Agreement after a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered a serious mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
At the summit meeting were the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, of Bolivia, Evo Morales, and of Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, who has been banned from prison since 2011 after the deposition of his president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit meeting in Lima shortly after lunchtime.
The Head of State read out the final document, which said that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were established over an investment amount of a total of 17 billion dollars.
On the decisions taken, he said that the countries of the Unasur will take "significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He said measures would be pushed forward to "improve cooperation in the fight against insecurity in the cities and against organised, transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act together and efficiently in the event of natural disasters."
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant features, but should serve to expand our production output and show our peoples a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects designed to improve spatial connections in South America, and especially in rural and border areas...and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms," the Peruvian president said in a read-out statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvians, which would be on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which are intended to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American nations," which it is currently excluded from.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was emphasised at the summit.
With that in mind, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico, to treat the maritime conflict respectfully after a judgment of the ICJ questioned by Bogotá.
"Possibly I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusionary, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilised and respectful as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the takeover of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers also met in advance to adopt the action plan for 2013, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, even if the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru is chairing the regional bloc.
